@node ID0_1 "Old ideas - assembly ? (ID0_1)"
From: jj@it.kth.se (Janne Johansson)
Subject: Re: Old ideas - assembly ?
Date: Tue, 01 Dec 1998 10:43:24 +0100

> > I know it's very boring. E is fast, really, but it doesn't optimize a
thing,
> > while C compilers do.
>
> Really? Do you mean in size or speed? A simple "Hello, world!" program in
> E becomes ~700 bytes large. In gcc it becomes >2000 bytes. (okay, I don't
> know if gcc is good or bad compiler)

gcc is probably the best codegenerator as long as you dont go wild on
systemcalls,
since it will put all arguments on the stack, but the collective experience
of
680x0 that the gcc guys have is hard to beat. Really.

The reason for the size is that "printf" will support all funky modes like
printing formatted strings ("my name is: %s age: %d") and so on. That is why
it takes 2k for hello world. You probably get stack-extension in the binary
also.

If you link against libnix (small startup code) and use PutStr() (whatever
its
name is) from dos.library, you end up with lots smaller files.

