Subject: Re: Old ideas - assembly ?

On Tue, 1 Dec 1998, Staf Verhaegen wrote:

=>Actually the compiler is so fast because E is a typeless language.

I would argue its speed came from its customized unflexible syntax parsing,
direct unoptimised binary output and the module/cache concept more than
anything else. But yes, every little helps.

=>A compiler written in C with FLEX and YACC and a good optimising compiler
will
=>not be that much slower.

On a fast computer, maybe. But on normal machines, E gives even the
assemblers
a good race for their money. C compilers aren't in with a chance.

Stuart

@endnode

