@node ID0_6 "Old ideas - assembly ? (ID0_6)"
Date: Tue, 1 Dec 1998 17:27:56 +0000 (BST)
From: sac@csd.abdn.ac.uk (Stuart Caie)
Subject: Re: Re[2]: Old ideas - assembly ?

On Tue, 1 Dec 1998, Maxim Olivier-Adlhoch wrote:

=>I agree with you, but You can be the most Brilliant programmer Ever and
JAVA will
=>still NEVER be fast ;-)  (I'm not saying that because your HW screams that
JAVA will
=>be responsive... I mean that relatively speaking, Java and Asm are at
different
=>speeds levels)

Not neccesarily. As you can see with the PPC, processors are more and more
being tuned to give best performance to compiler output and not waste time
by allowing 'tricks' which humans use to get better performance than a
highly optimising compiler wants to give! If you were a programming the
Java chip, your code would probably run not much faster than the compiler's
output for the same thing.

Stuart

@endnode

@node ID0_7 "Old ideas - assembly ? (ID0_7)"
Date: Tue, 01 Dec 1998 17:55:59 -0500
From: max2@ordigraphe.com ("Maxim Olivier-Adlhoch")
Subject: Re: Re[2]: Old ideas - assembly ?

Stuart Caie wrote:

> Not neccesarily. As you can see with the PPC, processors are more and more
> being tuned to give best performance to compiler output and not waste time
> by allowing 'tricks' which humans use to get better performance than a
> highly optimising compiler wants to give! If you were a programming the
> Java chip, your code would probably run not much faster than the
compiler's
> output for the same thing.

Yeah but the JAVA CHIP would views byte code as if it was a machine
opcode... its
simply a high-level CISC CPU/Interpreter...

I agree with you though that ASM is not a cure for all booboos, since some
programming tricks actually slow down modern CPUs... Because they use branch
predictions and stuff like that.  The CPU will be ready when a dumb
operation
occurs but can be caught off-guard when a pretty smart code arrives. this
can slow
it down.  But I think these cpu optimisations will affect database
management and
heavy datastructure useage more than math-based ops...

