@node ID1_2 "StackSwap (fwd) (ID1_2)"
From: carl.drougge@2.sbbs.se (Carl Drougge)
Date: Thu, 03 Dec 1998 23:14:14 +0100
Subject: Re: StackSwap (fwd)

Den 29-Nov-98, skrev Stefan Blixth:

>I'm trying to swap the stack of my program.
>The problem is that I don't know what the 'pointer'-field is supposed to
>keep. As I understand, the 'lower' and 'upper'-fields is the pointers to
>the lower and upper addresses of my allocated memoryblock.

>I've tried this:

>PROC main()
> DEF x, stack:stackswapstruct
> IF x:=New(64000)
>  stack.lower:=x
>  stack.upper:=x+64000
>  stack.pointer:=x+64000
>  StackSwap(stack)
>  -> code..
>  -> ..
>  StackSwap(stack)
> ENDIF
>ENDPROC

>This works sometimes, which means that somthing is wrong (I guess the
>'pointer') but I'm not sure!

You can't expect anything to work for the program with an empty stack! You
*must* copy the old one to the new one. And also the .pointer should point
to
where you want to be after StackSwap() return. That is to x+64000-usedstack.
Unfortunetely you can't find out how much of the stack is used in E, since
the
tc.spupper and tc.splower are not setup currectly.

But why do you need to swap the stack?
OPT STACK=64000
should work just fine. And if you spawn child-processes they are given their
own stack by CreateNewProc()..

@endnode

