(This is a repost. Sorry for the delay.)

ss37@irz301.inf.tu-dresden.de (Sven Steiniger) wrote:

> > > I think the only option is to rewrite the source code completely (even
in
> > > E) and adding new features as native instead of making E a bunch of
hacks
> > > and macros suited only for gcc maniacs (people in year 2000 cannot
still
>
> Do you really wanna write an complete compiler in E?

<cough>  Well, I do :)

I'm very pleased to see that more than three people are
willing to produce a portable E compiler. I didn't work on
it for quite some time now, this is what it actually does
(,does' in this context means: it parses and produces code
for it.):

- - functions with local variables and parameters
- - stucture declarations and access
- - class declarations and attribute access
- - method definitions (like functions above) [*]
- - basic arithmetics (+-*/)
- - function calls

[*] I didn't pass the instance pointer to the methdo,
otherwise the generated code should be okay. :)

That's about it, with one or two additions. Compilation is
done in two steps:

1) scanning and parsing. The generated syntax tree will be
written to disk *as is*. No assumptions about the language
to be generated is made.

2) reading the syntax tree and generating the code. The code
generator will do any optimizations at this stage.

The compiler is written in E (there is an earlier version in
C). The scanner is based on Wouters scanner which he
published in some E version as example source. The parser is
implemented using EYacc which can be easily converted to
Yacc/Bison/JavaYacc (each item parsed will be passed as
parameter to a function).

The early C version of the compiler had a code generator
that produced code for a simple register machine. The current
code generator in the E version produces C code which
compiles fine with GCC 2.7.2.1.

The idea is to make the compiler compile itself, of course.

If somebody wants to see the source: just mail me. It's a
mess but it works. I started with it when I didn't know a
single thing about building compilers, maybe I'd code some
things different now. However, it sure would be as OO as it is
now.

To compile it one needs my oo hierarchy (parts of it). Maybe
I should just upload all the stuff to my university
account...

Is somebody reading this list who has actually built a compiler
already? Not for E, any language would do, somebody who
knows something about compilers should maybe take a look it
the sources :)

  grEgor

P.S. Somebody mumbled about too much compiler mails on this
list. I prefixed the subject with "[EC]" so anyone who
doesn't want to read these mails can skip, delete or forward
them to an extra folder. Maybe this helps :)
