   The actuall problem is in synchronization... I have programmed robotics
on my
Amiga in the past (by using PowerTransistors and Stepper motors) and the
real pain
(in serial comms) is to get the external electronics to receive/send the
signals
in the right time...

   BUT this does not exist with normal parallel operation, there is a pin
which is
used to send a little signal to/From the computer that your device is now
READING
or WRITING to the computer... when the state CHANGES, both systems can
react...
the way I see the signal being sent (by your analysis at the top) I'd say
you
should plug the CLK pin to this R/W selector and you should ask the system
to read
the value at the port.  Then zero-in on the byte you want to read and glue
the
consecutive bytes up to the binary word lenght of the serial signal you are
transmitting...

Like a transcoder in fact...

If you are electronicly aware, you can EASILY build such a transcoder using
VERY
basic Flip-Flops... then every 7-8 bits (which I guess is your word length)
activate the R/W pin on the computer  :)

You can use parallel.device to work with above algorythm...  I'm not saying
I've
tried it... just that it is one potential solution...  ;)

When I say R/W I also mean that you must use the pulse, which tells system
that
there is 'new' data at the port (or more precisely within the BUS)... look
into
any digital Electronic book under RS-232 parallel port and it will describe
it in
detail... its quite easy , really.

